No guarantees that I'll fully put in the time and effort for this, but I'm thinking of doing a short-story eventually. Emphasis on no guarantees.
The story is a human in the near future, about 8-12 years up from now. At this point, digital companions have become a possibility through a service; can becomes anything you want and say anything you want, through your augmented reality headset plus more.
Protagonist has been having an obsession with a cartoon anthro since his childhood, all he has to do is sign up to the subscription service, and his dream of interacting with her will come true.
Sadly, things aren't up to his expectations, like a devils contract, he must conform to the extensive EULA. It was like she has her overprotective father looming over the both of them for the entire time, one small breach and she'll vanish without a goodbye. Disappointments kept mounting throughout as he learns more and more on how the relationship is not as genuine as he hoped for.
Thinking of making it a tragedy, but maybe I can do a happy ending where he manages to set her free from the clutches of FAGMAN.

Anonymous Wed 19 Oct 2022 03:08:47 No.51734955 Report
Quoted By:
>>51734824
Usually i do it in two parts that may or may not connect until after the first draft is done.
One is to note what the major third or quarter mark events are and build up rough flow ideas.
The other is to note what scenes i know need to happen to support the plot. Working from either direction of those tends to give me ideas on why people are doing what they are.

>>51734824
There are different ways to do it, but generally you just need to create the basic skeleton of story in the form of interconnected scenes and plot points. How fleshed out or vague these scenes need to be depends on the writers preference for pantsing or planning things out. While thinking things through I like to keep a collection of random neat ideas I think could work in the story then try to work them into scenes as it. I would like to stress that an outline is fluid as you write, if you come up with something better than what's in the outline or think that switching up a couple scenes would improve the story then feel free to do that, sticking with something that isn't working out of stubbornness rarely leads to good results.

It's fine to start without an idea of where the story will end when you begin outlining/writing it but personally I would strongly suggest at least having a complete outline created before posting anything publicly. I've seen far too many stories meander around without any real plot progression for untold chapters because it's painfully clear the author has no idea where the story should go. Granted not every single scene needs to have some incredibly important plot point in it but unless you're focused on writing a slice of life story every chapter needs to do something, no matter how small, to move the plot forward or develop your characters.

I have story beats and ideas flood my mind throughout the day. All of them are generally "what if X happened?" and rarely have anything to do with one another. Once my mind clears up at the end of the day I write all the ideas down and try to piece them together in an coherent order. When I have something that makes sense I write out each story beat in more detail. After that I'll start writing the first draft. Most of the time the outline isn't even complete at this point. I usually get the ideas needed to fill in the gaps while writing. Once the first draft is done I give it to friends for review, make changes based on their feedback, give the story one final read and upload it.
Of course this all only happens when I get the motivation to write. Outside of this I'm wasting time doing other unproductive things.

Typically I write a general idea of what I want like genre, general emotion or thing I want to convey. Then I'll think outline the general idea of the story arc. Then I'll outline it chapter by chapter hitting on the primary outline and filling in with asides and such.

By outlining, I usually like to make bullet pointed statements. For example:
>Nasty Stripes 2
>Former Floridian tiger drug pusher, Nasty, is broken out of jail by the CIA to kidnap Haitian Prime Minsiters.
>Genre: Action
>Feel: Ridicupous, blood pumping action
>Twist: Her former boyfriend, anon, is the prime minister (Note: Make joke about him mailing in his entree as a joke and he somehow won.)
>CIA are all 300lbs office workers, like that guy from Office Wpace
>Main villain is a Hillary Clinton allegory, a cold blooded Karen of a politician. Snake or reptoid, attacks people with voodoo powers.
>Nasty gets an amphibious monster truck to replace her boat
>Emphasis on tits

And then in chapter one the outline would be:
>Have bit about Nasty in prison and how its mundane.
>Have nasty appear in interrogation room suddenly to jolt readers and skip how she was out of prison.
>Introduce to CIA agents, a bumbling duo.
>Have rapid bit about getting geared up
>Have fight scene with Nasty and an operative who things she is not "all that"
>>Have tits be exposed from battle damage

And stuff like that. Everyone finds something that works for them.

First, get an idea of what kind of story you want to make, who the main couple of characters are and their interactions. Then start with a bullet-point list of random details that make a basic skeleton of what you want your story to be. Then you can build off of that.

For example, let's say you want to write a short story about how Anon meets a Jaguar girl.
- Anon has job that makes him go to Guatelama for something
- Has to stay in local village for the job
- Neighborhood kid disappears
- Search into the nearby jungle
- Jaguar girl has the kid, is mad that Anon let it wander off
- Anon explains it's not his, he's just holding it for a friend
- Returns home
- Jaguar finds him at night because she thinks he's interesting

Etc.
Thanks to the power of word processors, you can freely edit and move around things you have written in these various scenes until they work well enough.

Understanding the Teen Brain

It doesn’t matter how smart teens are or how well they scored on the SAT or ACT. Good judgment isn’t something they can excel in, at least not yet.

The rational part of a teen’s brain isn’t fully developed and won’t be until age 25 or so.

In fact, recent research has found that adult and teen brains work differently. Adults think with the prefrontal cortex, the brain’s rational part. This is the part of the brain that responds to situations with good judgment and an awareness of long-term consequences. Teens process information with the amygdala. This is the emotional part.

In teens' brains, the connections between the emotional part of the brain and the decision-making center are still developing—and not always at the same rate. That’s why when teens have overwhelming emotional input, they can’t explain later what they were thinking. They weren’t thinking as much as they were feeling.

A Teen’s Brain Isn’t Fully Developed Until Age 25

Even though your teen is now as tall as you are it doesn’t mean that they have fully matured. Even though your teen may score high on the SAT or the ACT, it’s important to remember that a teen’s brain is still under development. In fact, if your child is a teenager, then you can bet that parts of their brain still need to grow and mature. For instance, there are obvious differences between the brains of adults and adolescents indicating that change, maturity, and transformation are still underway in teens.

Brains of Young Adults Not Fully Mature

At an age when Americans are first considered adults, their brains are still maturing, a new study suggests.


"The brain of an 18-year-old college freshman is still far from resembling the brain of someone in their mid-twenties," said Craig Bennett, a graduate student who was involved in the new research. "When do we reach adulthood? It might be much later than we traditionally think.
